{
  "style": "",
  "texts": [
    "Based on these results, we make the following observations: First, GNN-based retrieval is both more efficient (in terms of the number of KG tokens) and more effective (in terms of F1 score) than both RoG and SubgraphRAG, particularly for complex questions such as those from CWQ.",
    "Second, GNN-based retrieval demonstrates superior performance, surpassing RoG and SubgraphRAG by 26.1-27.0% points in terms of Hit@1.",
    "Third, retrieval augmentation (denoted as GNN-RAG+RA) enhances both Hit@k and KGQA F1 scores, as it enables the combination of non-overlapping knowledge graph information from GNN-based and semantic parsing (RoG) retrieval, leading to an increase in the number of input tokens and thereby improving the LLM's contextual understanding.",
    "GNN-RAG+RA is more efficient than long-context alternatives as SubgraphRAG.",
    "In Table 4, we present an ablation study of GNN hyperparameters (number of layers L and number of question embeddings K) and techniques (with or without iterative reasoning) for GNN-RAG."
  ],
